Although not entirely specific, cytomorphologic features that favor reactive pneumocytes rather than adenocarcinoma include the following 10 , 20 , 21 , 22 , 23 :
Population of cells with a spectrum of atypia, rather than two distinct populations of benign‐appearing and malignant‐appearing cells 10 , 21 , 22 , 24 , 25 , 26 , 27 , 28 ;
Vacuolization of the cytoplasm or binucleation;
Cytomegaly with preservation of the N:C ratio; and
Protrusion of nuclei over a flat cellular contour (so‐called Napoleon hat shape). 20

Table 2 summarizes cytologic features that help differentiate benign reactive atypia from well differentiated adenocarcinomas (adapted from The Art and Science of Cytopathology by Richard Mac DeMay
18
). Figures 2, 3, and 4 showcase the features listed above.

Reactive cytologic changes can appear within weeks of starting treatment and typically resolve within a month after treatment concludes. However, radiation‐induced atypia may persist for years after exposure. 30 , 33 Key cytologic features of radiation‐related atypia include:
Concordant nuclear and cytoplasmic enlargement, resulting in a normal to only mildly increased N:C ratio;
Smudgy chromatin and irregular nuclear membranes, which may mimic malignancy;
Inconspicuous nucleoli;
Rare or absent mitotic figures; and
Nuclear pleomorphism, generally less pronounced compared with that in malignant cells(Table 3). 10 , 11 , 15 , 21 , 22 , 26 , 27 , 33
